<font color="#FF0000">REALITY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  2  6:36:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The insinuation that the American leaders sent 57,600 Americans to their deaths out of sympathy for the poor Vietnamese people is so rediculous I can't imagine someone actually saying it. If we were motivated by sympathy for the Vietnamese people, why are we not motivated by sympathy for the Nigerian people? Why are the Vietnamese people worthy of such hardship and sacrifice on our part whereas the Nigerian people are not worthy of this? Why didn't the same altruistic compassion that caused us to die for the poor Vietnamese people not cause us to go to war and die for the poor Nigerian people? What's so special about the Vietnamese people? What is the secret mysterious special thing about the Vietnamese people that would specifically cause their hardship and plight to so deeply move the American leaders that they would send 57,600 Americans to their deaths on their behalf while not sending anyone to die trying to free the poor people in Nigeria? If we were truly motivated by altruistic compassion, we would not view the plight of the Vietnamese to warrant our intervention, and simultaneously consider the plight of the Nigerians to not warrant our intervention. I'm just using Nigeria as an example of one of dozens of brutal dictatorships with which we have very friendly relations. Why were the South Vietnamese specifically singled out as being worthy of having 57,600 Americans die on their behalf? If you were truly motivated by love of your fellow man, you wouldn't care what country someone was a citizen of. Of course, the American leaders were never moved to action out of sympathy for the Vietnamese people. They wanted to establish a puppet government loyal to Washington. The two superpowers were fighting over this tiny country. Each wanted to rule it. That's the only reason we were involved.<br><br>
Nigeria is ruled by General Sani Abacha, head of one of the most bloodthirsty regimes on the planet. Despite this, we don't have an embargo against Nigeria. We don't have sanctions against Nigeria. The reason is because politicians are under the influence of American oil companies which would loose money otherwise. Is this the action of a country that cares about the suffering of people around the world? If we were so concerned about human rights, why do we have such friendly relations with Nigeria which has killed staggering numbers of people in political persecution?<br><br>
We also have friendly relations with Burma which is guilty of horrendous human rights abuses. Tanker said in his post that this was in a different &quot;time frame&quot; than Vietnam, meaning more recently, implying that at the time of Vietnam we were compassionate towards others but have since become cold hearted. During the 1960's and 1970's, Burma was a military dictatorship ruled by Ne Win. This was during the same time period as Vietnam. Therefore the claim that American involvement in Vietnam was motivated by American leader's inability to see fellow human beings suffer is contradicted by the fact that they did nothing to help those in Burma. Tanker said that this was not &quot;the case during the time frame of Vietnam&quot;. I believe the 1960's and 1970's was when the Vietnam War occurred. Similarly, from 1965 to 1977 Indonesia was a military dictatorship ruled by General Suharto. He was a bloodthirsty dictator who slaughtered one million of his own citizens. Tanker also claims that this happened in a different &quot;time frame&quot; from Vietnam, and the fact Americans did nothing about it doesn't imply that the Vietnam War wasn't fought because the American leaders couldn't stand to see other people in the world treated poorly.<br><br>
I tried to give George Bush the benefit of the doubt when referring to the Persian Gulf War. Bush always claimed that the Persian Gulf War was fought to restore one of the only absolute monarchies on the planet. Of course we all know thast what he did was much worse, which was kill all of these people so Americans wouldn't have to pay so much for gasoline. In the Persian Gulf War, we slaughtered 200,000 people, including 100,000 civilians, including 35,000 children. The official reason was to restore one of the only absolute monarchies on the planet. The real reason was so Americans wouldn't have to pay so much for gasoline. The American people were euphoric, not despite, but because of the fact that we delibrately slaughtered hundreds of thousands of completely innocent people. I apologize for taking George Bush at his word, that we were there to restore a monarchy. You're right, what we did was much worse. We weren't even there to establish that it was wrong to annex your neighbors. We killed all of these people simply so Americans wouldn't have to pay so much for gasoline.<br><br>
Turkey is guilty of heinous human rights abuses. I'll just give a recent example. We get angry when Saddam Hussain kills Kurds in his country. We don't care when President Ozal of Turkey kills Kurds in his country. The Turkish government frequently rounds up people just because they're Kurds and kills them. Yet they don't stop there. They unilaterally invade Iraq for the purpose of killing the Kurds in Iraq. Not only that, but they kill the Kurds in the northern protected zone of Iraq. Those Kurds were supposedly under the protection of the United States. The fine print is that we were there to protect the Kurds only from Saddam and not from any of our allies who chose to go in there and kill them. Turkey invaded Cyprus. The Turks in Cyprus have been viscious to the Greeks in Cyprus. Turkey is notorious for human rights abuses. Despite this, Turkey is one of our tightest allies. Is this the act of a country that cares about human rights?<br><br>
In Chile, in 1970, Salvador Allende became the first Marxist ever to win a free federal election. He nationalized U.S. copper firms and private banks. He died in a military coup backed by the CIA, and was replaced by a junta headed by General Augusto Pinochet. The United States replaced a democratically elected leader with a military dictator. That's exactly what we did. Think about that for momment. There are people who claim that the United States cares about democracy and freedom? In the 1980's, El Salvador was ruled by a military junta led by Napolean Duarte. The junta killed at least 35,000 civilians between 1979 and 1983, including Archbishop Oscar Romero. They slaughtered whole villages, and delibrately targeted Catholic clergy, which they perceived to be &quot;leftist&quot;. Some of those invloved in the death squads were trained by the United States. The junta always received very strong loyal support from the United States. Is this an example of the United States caring about human rights?<br><br>
The reason the United States fought the Spanish-American War was to try to steal this land from Spain. We wanted to rule Puerto Rico, Cuba, Guam and the Philippines. The people in the Philippines were so naive they actually thought they'd be granted their freedom. We used military force to crush their attempt to become free. It was territorial expansion. It was a land grab like the Mexican-American War, or when Saddam annexed Kuwait. During the Mexican-American War, Henry Davis Thoreau and others heraled as heroes those soldiers who threw down their guns and refused to fight for such an evil purpose.<br><br>
The United States did not want to enter World War I. We were very strongly against entering the war. However Germany sank American ships in the process of trying to break the blockade against it. Americans died on foreign ships sank by the Germans. On May 8, 1915, the Germans sank the Lusitania which carried many Americans. The main reason this hit a raw nerve among the American public is because it reminded them of the Titanic. When Americans learned of communication between Germany and Mexico, which was essentially meaningless and irrelevant, they finally relented to British and French pressure to join the war.<br><br>
The United States did not want to enter World War II. The singular reason we finally entered the war is because Japan bombed Pearl Habor. The main reason Americans were so horror striken at the attack on Pearl Habor is because Japan hadn't declared war first, as if that detail made it much worse. The only reason the United States declared war on Germany and Italy is because Germany and Italy declared war on the United States. If Japan hadn't bombed Pearl Habor, we would never have entered the war, unless in the unlikely event Germany was ever in a position to attack the United States.<br><br>
When the president of the United States was officially Ronald Reagan, those who actually ran the White House were devoted to making him look good. Usually they did a good job but once they blundered miserably. Several American soldiers were killed in a terrorist attack in Lebanon. The people in charge of Reagan were nervous this would make him look bad. They needed a diversion. They decided to attack a tiny island in the West Indies. They thought that by attacking a tiny island, it would make Reagan look good. Instead, by implying that a tiny island was somehow a threat to the United States, it only made the United States look weak. Grenada has an area of 120 square miles, and a population of 112,000 people. It had literally no military whatsoever. Despite the fact that the tiny island we were attacking had no military at all, several Americans were killed simply by crashing their helicopters into the ground. By saying that this tiny island was a threat to the United States, they were saying that the United States is the weakest country in the world. Pat Buchannan may believe that but I don't believe that. Therefore Reagan's handlers misjudged the situation and it backfired horribly.<br><br>
There are many instances in which there is a third world conflict. It could be a war between nations, or it could be a rebellion within a nation. Each side obtains a superpower sponsor that supplies them with money, weapons, intelligence, troops, or support. Examples include Korea, Vietnam, Afganistan, Nicaragua, El Salvador, and Angola. The local third world participants aren't fighting because of the Cold War. They are fighting for whatever reason they are fighting in the first place. However the superpowers grant sponsorship because of the Cold War. The superpowers imagine themselves fighting each other through their proxies. The superpowers imagine a world map, and each wants to control as much of it as possible. That's the only reason they did this. If we intervened in Vietnam out of sympathy for the people, why did that same sympathy not cause us to intervene in Nigeria, Burma, Indonesia, and elsewhere in the world?
